======================================================================
PART 1: FIBONACCI NUMBERS AND TOURNAMENT PRIMES
======================================================================

Fibonacci sequence and primality:

  F_ 1 =      1
  F_ 2 =      1
  F_ 3 =      2 ← TOURNAMENT PRIME!
  F_ 4 =      3 ← TOURNAMENT PRIME!
  F_ 5 =      5 ← TOURNAMENT PRIME!
  F_ 6 =      8
  F_ 7 =     13 (prime)
  F_ 8 =     21
  F_ 9 =     34
  F_10 =     55
  F_11 =     89 (prime)
  F_12 =    144
  F_13 =    233 (prime)
  F_14 =    377
  F_15 =    610
  F_16 =    987
  F_17 =   1597 (prime)
  F_18 =   2584
  F_19 =   4181

  Fibonacci PRIMES: F₃=2, F₄=3, F₅=5, F₇=13, F₁₁=89, F₁₃=233, ...
  The first three: 2, 3, 5 = the tournament triple!
  Indices of Fibonacci primes: 3, 4, 5, 7, 11, 13, ...
    These indices are themselves mostly prime (Wall conjecture)

Lucas numbers L_n = φⁿ + ψⁿ (companion to Fibonacci):
  L_ 0 =      2 = KEY₁
  L_ 1 =      1
  L_ 2 =      3 = KEY₂
  L_ 3 =      4
  L_ 4 =      7 = rank(E₇)
  L_ 5 =     11
  L_ 6 =     18 = h(E₇)!
  L_ 7 =     29
  L_ 8 =     47 = prime
  L_ 9 =     76
  L_10 =    123 = 3·41
  L_11 =    199

  REMARKABLE: L₀ = 2 = KEY₁, L₁ = 1, L₂ = 3 = KEY₂
  L₆ = 18 = h(E₇)!
  The Lucas numbers start with the two keys!
  And L₆ = 18 is the Coxeter number of E₇!

======================================================================
PART 2: COXETER RATIOS AS FIBONACCI CONVERGENTS
======================================================================

Coxeter number ratios and Fibonacci fractions:

  h(F₄)/h(G₂) = 12/6 = 2 = F_3/F_2
  h(E₆)/h(F₄) = 12/12 = 1 = F_2/F_1
  h(E₇)/h(E₆) = 18/12 = 3/2 = F_4/F_3
  h(E₈)/h(E₇) = 30/18 = 5/3 = F_5/F_4

  The ratios: 2/1, 1/1, 3/2, 5/3
  = F₃/F₂, F₁/F₁, F₄/F₃, F₅/F₄

  Product of all ratios = 5 = 5.0
  = h(E₈)/h(G₂) = 30/6 = 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂

  These fractions converge to φ = 1.6180339887:
    2/1 = 2.0   (above φ)
    1/1 = 1.0   (below φ)
    3/2 = 1.5   (below φ)
    5/3 = 1.667 (above φ)

  Average ratio = 37/24 ≈ 1.541667
  φ = 1.618034
  φ² = 2.618034
  The average ≈ φ²/2 + 1/(2φ)... hmm, not exact

  Geometric mean = 5^(1/4) = 1.495349 = 1.495349
  (Since product = 5, geometric mean = 5^(1/(#ratios)))
  5^(1/4) = 1.495349 ≈ φ^(3/4) = 1.434633... close!

======================================================================
PART 3: φ IN THE INDEPENDENCE POLYNOMIAL
======================================================================

Independence polynomial I(P,x) = 1 + 10x + 30x² + 30x³ + 5x⁴

  After substitution u = x + 1/x:
  I(P,x)/x² = 5(u² + 6u + 4)
  Roots: u = -3 ± √5

  u₁ = -3 + √5 = -0.7639320225
  u₂ = -3 - √5 = -5.2360679775

  Expressing in terms of φ:
    φ = (1+√5)/2 = 1.6180339887
    √5 = 2φ - 1
    u₁ = -3 + (2φ-1) = 2φ - 4 = 2(φ - 2) = 2(φ - KEY₁)
    u₂ = -3 - (2φ-1) = -2 - 2φ = -2(1+φ) = -2φ²

    u₁ = 2(φ-KEY₁) = -0.7639320225
    u₂ = -2φ²       = -5.2360679775

  The four roots of I(P,x) = 0:
    From u=-0.7639: x = -0.3820+0.9242j, -0.3820-0.9242j (complex, |x|=1.000000)
    From u=-5.2361: x = -0.19850884, -5.03755914 (real)

  Complex roots lie on the UNIT CIRCLE |x| = 1
  This is related to the fact that Petersen is vertex-transitive

  Real roots: -0.1985088357 and -5.0375591418
  Product: 1.0000000000 (should be 1)
  Sum: -5.2360679775 = u₂ = -2φ²

  r₁ = (-φ² + √(φ⁴-1))/1 ≈ -0.198509
  r₂ = (-φ² - √(φ⁴-1))/1 ≈ -5.037559
  |r₂| = 5.037559
  |r₂| = φ² + √(φ⁴-1) ≈ 5.037559
  φ⁴ = 6.854102 = (φ²)² = (φ+1)² = φ²+2φ+1 = 3φ+2
  φ⁴ - 1 = 3φ+1 = 5.854102

======================================================================
PART 4: THE GOLDEN RATIO IN E₈ — H₃ AND ICOSIANS
======================================================================

The non-crystallographic Coxeter group H₃:
  H₃ is the symmetry group of the icosahedron
  |H₃| = 120 = |BI| = |S₅|
  H₃ has Coxeter matrix with entries 2, 3, 5
  The eigenvalues of H₃'s Cartan matrix involve φ

  The H₃ Coxeter diagram:  o---o===o
                           3   5
  (edge label 5 means angle π/5 between mirrors)

  cos(π/5) = φ/2 = 0.809017
  cos(2π/5) = (φ-1)/2 = 1/(2φ) = 0.309017
  The golden ratio IS the cosine structure of the pentagon!

  H₄ (4D icosahedral symmetry) and E₈:
    |H₄| = 14400 = 120² = |BI|²
    14400 = 2⁵·3²·5² = KEY₁⁵·KEY₂²·(KEY₁+KEY₂)²
    H₄ has exponents {1, 11, 19, 29}
    = all four CORNERS of E₈ exponent set!
    E₈ exponents: {1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29}
    H₄ exponents are positions 1, 3, 6, 8 of E₈ list

  The H₄ exponents {1,11,19,29} satisfy:
    Sum: 1+11+19+29 = 60 = |A₅| = |BI|/2
    Product: 1·11·19·29 = 6061 = h(E₈)·202
    Pairs sum to 30: 1+29=30, 11+19=30
    ALL pairs sum to h(E₈)!

  ICOSIANS (Hamilton, 1856):
    Quaternions with coefficients in Z[φ]
    120 unit icosians form a group ≅ BI
    When embedded in R⁸ via Z[φ] → R², they generate E₈
    φ is the BRIDGE from H₃ to E₈!

  The embedding map:
    Z[φ] → R²: a+bφ ↦ (a+bφ, a+bψ) where ψ = (1-√5)/2
    Quaternion q ∈ Z[φ]⁴ maps to R⁸
    The image of the 120 unit icosians = the 240 shortest E₈ vectors
    (each icosian maps to 2 E₈ vectors via the ±ψ embeddings)

  THIS IS WHY #roots(E₈) = 2·|BI| = 240:
    Each of the 120 icosians has 2 Galois conjugates
    240 = 2·120 = KEY₁·|BI|

======================================================================
PART 5: φ AS THE BRIDGE BETWEEN KEY₁ AND KEY₂
======================================================================

The golden ratio φ = (1+√5)/2 connects KEY₁ and KEY₂:

  φ ≈ 1.6180339887
  KEY₁ = 2, KEY₂ = 3
  KEY₁ < φ² < KEY₂ (since φ² = φ+1 ≈ 2.618)

  KEY₁·KEY₂ = 6, √(KEY₁·KEY₂) = √6 ≈ 2.449490
  φ² = φ+1 ≈ 2.618034
  φ² is between √6 and KEY₂ = 3

  φ = [1; 1, 1, 1, ...] (slowest converging CF)
  KEY₂/KEY₁ = 3/2 = [1; 2] (finite CF)
  φ is the 'most irrational' number between KEY₁ and KEY₂

  Stern-Brocot mediants between 1 and 2:
    1/1 ← 3/2 → 2/1
    3/2 = KEY₂/KEY₁ is the mediant of 1/1 and 2/1
    The SIMPLEST fraction between 1 and 2
    In music: the perfect fifth, most consonant after the octave

  φ satisfies x² = x + 1, i.e., x² - x - 1 = 0
  Tournament polynomial: x² - 5x + 6 = 0
  Compare:
    φ poly: x² - x - 1 = 0 (roots φ, ψ)
    f poly: x² - 5x + 6 = 0 (roots 2, 3)

  The φ polynomial has:
    sum of roots = 1, product = -1
  The f polynomial has:
    sum of roots = 5, product = 6

  Ratio: sum_f/sum_φ = 5/1 = KEY₁+KEY₂
  Ratio: prod_f/prod_φ = 6/(-1) = -6 = -h(G₂)

  Golden recurrence: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2)
    General solution: A·φⁿ + B·ψⁿ
    Dominant: φⁿ (since |φ| > |ψ|)

  (2,3) recurrence: a(n) = 5a(n-1) - 6a(n-2)
    General solution: A·2ⁿ + B·3ⁿ
    Dominant: 3ⁿ (since 3 > 2)

  PARALLEL:
    Fibonacci: roots φ,ψ with |φ/ψ| = φ² ≈ 2.618
    Tournament: roots 2,3 with |3/2| = 1.5
    The golden ratio φ² ≈ 2.618 sits between KEY₂/KEY₁ = 1.5 and KEY₂ = 3

======================================================================
PART 6: THE (2,3,5) AS FIBONACCI PRIMES
======================================================================

The triple (2,3,5) = (F₃, F₄, F₅) — three consecutive Fibonacci numbers!

  F₁ = 1, F₂ = 1, F₃ = 2, F₄ = 3, F₅ = 5, F₆ = 8, F₇ = 13

  The triple (F₃, F₄, F₅) = (2, 3, 5) uniquely satisfies:
    a + b = c (Fibonacci rule)
    All three are prime
    a·b·c = 30 = h(E₈)

  Other consecutive Fibonacci triples with all prime:
    (F_3, F_4, F_5) = (2, 3, 5)

  ONLY (2, 3, 5) works!
  Because F₆ = 8 = 2³ is not prime.
  And for n≥7, at least one of F_n, F_{n+1}, F_{n+2} is even (divisible by KEY₁)

  Fibonacci modulo 2: 1 1 0 1 1 0 1 1 0 1 1 0 1 1 0 1 1 0 1 
  Period 3: (1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, ...)
  Every 3rd Fibonacci number is even (divisible by KEY₁)
  3 = KEY₂ is the Fibonacci period mod KEY₁!

  Fibonacci modulo 3: 1 1 2 0 2 2 1 0 1 1 2 0 2 2 1 0 1 1 2 
  Period 8: (1,1,2,0,2,2,1,0,...)
  Every 4th Fibonacci number is divisible by KEY₂=3
  Pisano period π(3) = 8 = rank(E₈)!

  Fibonacci modulo 5: 1 1 2 3 0 3 3 1 4 0 4 4 3 2 0 2 2 4 1 
  Period 20: ...
  Every 5th Fibonacci number is divisible by KEY₁+KEY₂=5
  Pisano period π(5) = 20 = V(dodecahedron) = f(7)!

  PISANO PERIODS (period of F_n mod m):
    π(  2) =    3 = KEY₂
    π(  3) =    8 = rank(E₈)
    π(  5) =   20 = V(dodec)
    π(  6) =   24 = |BT|
    π( 10) =   60 = |A₅|
    π( 30) =  120 = |BI| = |S₅|!

  π(30) = π(h(E₈)) = 120 = |BI| = |Aut(Petersen)|!
  The Fibonacci period mod h(E₈) IS the icosahedral group order!

  π(KEY₁) = KEY₂ = 3
  π(KEY₂) = rank(E₈) = 8
  π(KEY₁·KEY₂) = |BT| = 24
  π(KEY₁·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)) = |BI| = 120

======================================================================
FINAL: THE FIBONACCI-PETERSEN-LIE TRIANGLE
======================================================================

Three vertices of the universal triangle:

       FIBONACCI
      /         \
   φ→2          (2,3,5) = (F₃,F₄,F₅)
    /             \
 PETERSEN -------- LIE
   K(5,2)    E₆,E₇,E₈

Edges:
  Fibonacci → Petersen: π(30)=120=|Aut(P)|, I(P) factors via φ
  Fibonacci → Lie:      (2,3,5)=tournament triple, 2·3·5=h(E₈)
  Petersen → Lie:       eigenvalues {3,1,-2}, complement 30 edges

Center:
  The tournament polynomial f(z) = (z-2)(z-3)
  lives at the CENTER of this triangle,
  connecting all three worlds through z²-5z+6=0.
